key-EG.ELC.RNEW.ZS-climate.def: Renewable electricity is the share of electrity generated by renewable power plants in total electricity generated by all types of plants.
key-EG.ELC.RNEW.ZS-climate.name: Renewable electricity output (% of total)

key-EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-climate.def: Renewable energy consumption is the share of renewables energy in total final energy consumption.
key-EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-climate.name: Renewable energy consumption (% of total)
key-EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-climate.source: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from the SE4ALL Global Tracking Framework led jointly by the World Bank, International Energy Agency, and the Energy Sector Management Assistance Program.
key-EG.FEC.RNEW.ZS-climate.dataset: World Bank, Sustainable Energy for All (SE4ALL) database from the SE4ALL Global Tracking Framework led jointly by the World Bank, International Energy Agency, and the Energy Sector Management Assistance Program.

key-EG.IMP.CONS.ZS-climate.def: Net energy imports are estimated as energy use less production, both measured in oil equivalents. A negative value indicates that the country is a net exporter. Energy use refers to use of primary energy before transformation to other end-use fuels, which is equal to indigenous production plus imports and stock changes, minus exports and fuels supplied to ships and aircraft engaged in international transport.
key-EG.IMP.CONS.ZS-climate.name: Energy imports, net (% of energy use)

key-EN.ATM.CO2E.KT-climate.def: Carbon dioxide emissions are those stemming from the burning of fossil fuels and the manufacture of cement. They include carbon dioxide produced during consumption of solid, liquid, and gas fuels and gas flaring.
key-EN.ATM.CO2E.KT-climate.name: CO2 Emissions (kt)
key-EN.ATM.CO2E.KT-climate.source: Data for up to 1990 are sourced from Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center, Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Tennessee, United States. Data from 1990 are CAIT data: Climate Watch. 2020. GHG Emissions. Washington, DC: World Resources Institute. Available at: https://www.climatewatchdata.org/ghg-emissions.
key-EN.ATM.CO2E.KT-climate.dataset: Data for up to 1990 are sourced from Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center, Environmental Sciences Division, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Tennessee, United States. Data from 1990 are CAIT data: Climate Watch. 2020. GHG Emissions. Washington, DC: World Resources Institute. Available at: https://www.climatewatchdata.org/ghg-emissions.
key-EN.ATM.CO2E.KT-climate.units: thousand metric tons of CO2 excluding Land-Use Change and Forestry

key-EN.CLC.DRSK.XQ-climate.def: Disaster risk reduction progress score is an average of self-assessment scores, ranging from 1 to 5, submitted by countries under Priority 1 of the Hyogo Framework National Progress Reports. The Hyogo Framework is a global blueprint for disaster risk reduction efforts that was adopted by 168 countries in 2005. Assessments of "Priority 1" include four indicators that reflect the degree to which countries have prioritized disaster risk reduction and the strengthening of relevant institutions.
key-EN.CLC.DRSK.XQ-climate.name: Disaster risk reduction progress score

key-ER.PTD.TOTL.ZS-climate.def: Terrestrial protected areas are totally or partially protected areas of at least 1,000 hectares that are designated by national authorities as scientific reserves with limited public access, national parks, natural monuments, nature reserves or wildlife sanctuaries, protected landscapes, and areas managed mainly for sustainable use. Marine protected areas are areas of intertidal or subtidal terrain--and overlying water and associated flora and fauna and historical and cultural features--that have been reserved by law or other effective means to protect part or all of the enclosed environment. Sites protected under local or provincial law are excluded.
key-ER.PTD.TOTL.ZS-climate.name: Terrestrial and marine protected areas (% of total territorial area)
key-ER.PTD.TOTL.ZS-climate.source: World Database on Protected Areas (WDPA) where the compilation and management is carried out by United Nations Environment World Conservation Monitoring Centre (UNEP-WCMC) in collaboration with governments, non-governmental organizations, academia and industry. The data is available online through the Protected Planet website (https://www.protectedplanet.net/).
key-ER.PTD.TOTL.ZS-climate.dataset: World Database on Protected Areas (WDPA) where the compilation and management is carried out by United Nations Environment World Conservation Monitoring Centre (UNEP-WCMC) in collaboration with governments, non-governmental organizations, academia and industry. The data is available online through the Protected Planet website (https://www.protectedplanet.net/).

key-hdr181606-climate.def: Measure of the aggregate extinction risk across groups of species. It is based on genuine changes in the number of species in each category of extinction risk on the International Union for Conservation of Nature Red List of Threatened Species. It ranges from 0, all species categorized as extinct, to 1, all species categorized as least concern.
key-hdr181606-climate.name: Red List Index
key-hdr181606-climate.source: United Nations Statistics Division (2020a). Global SDG Indicators Database. https://unstats.un.org/sdgs/indicators/database/. Accessed 21 July 2020.
key-hdr181606-climate.dataset: United Nations Statistics Division (2020a). Global SDG Indicators Database. https://unstats.un.org/sdgs/indicators/database/. Accessed 21 July 2020.

key-hdr97306-climate.def: Monetary valuation of energy, mineral and forest depletion, expressed as a percentage of gross national income (GNI).
key-hdr97306-climate.name: Natural resource depletion (% of GNI)
key-hdr97306-climate.source: World Bank (2020a). World Development Indicators database. Washington, DC. http://data.worldbank.org. Accessed 22 July 2020.
key-hdr97306-climate.dataset: World Bank (2020a). World Development Indicators database. Washington, DC. http://data.worldbank.org. Accessed 22 July 2020.

key-nd-gain-climate.def: The Notre Dame-Global Adaptation Index (ND-GAIN) Country Index is a free open source index that shows a country’s current vulnerability to climate disruptions. It also assesses a country’s readiness to leverage private and public sector investment for adaptive actions. ND-GAIN brings together over 74 variables to form 45 core indicators to measure vulnerability and readiness. ND-GAIN’s framework breaks the measure of vulnerability into exposure, sensitivity and adaptive capacity, and the measure of readiness into economic, governance and  social components.
key-nd-gain-climate.name: Global Adaptation Index (ND-GAIN)

key-nd-readiness-climate.def: Readiness to make effective use of investments for adaptation actions thanks to a safe and efficient business environment ND-GAIN measures readiness by considering a country’s ability to leverage investments to adaptation actions. ND-GAIN measures overall readiness by considering three components: economic readiness, governance readiness and social readiness.
key-nd-readiness-climate.name: Adaptation Readiness Index

key-nd-vulnerability-climate.def: Vulnerability is the propensity or predisposition of human societies to be negatively impacted by climate hazards. ND-GAIN assesses the vulnerability of a country by considering six life-supporting sectors: food, water, health, ecosystem services, human habitat and infrastructure. Each sector is in turn represented by six indicators that represent three cross-cutting components: the exposure of the sector to climate-related or climate-exacerbated hazards; the sensitivity of that sector to the impacts of the hazard and the adaptive capacity of the sector to cope or adapt to these impacts
key-nd-vulnerability-climate.name: Climate Vulnerability Index
